profile.name: Darren Close
profile.title: Data Entry, Web Scraping and QA Professional
profile.description: Am a a Computer Science Graduate who had accumulated many skills though years of education and self teaching. I am an expert with a keyboard and can type up to 115 WPM accurately making me a perfect candidate for all data entry tasks. I have also been freelancing for 3 years now and within that time I have carried out multiple web scraping/researching tasks. I am a qualified QA Engineer so I can carry out expert testing both in the manual and automated fields. I am sure if you have a project I can help you at a reasonable price!

skills.name: data-entry
skills.description: A data entry clerk, sometimes called a typist, is a member of staff employed to type data into a database using a keyboard. The keyboards used can often have specialist keys and multiple colours to help them in the task and speed up the work.

skills.name: web-scraping
skills.description: Web scraping (also called web harvesting or web data extraction) is a computer software technique of extracting information from websites.

skills.name: qa-engineering
skills.description: Quality Assurance (QA) is a way of preventing mistakes or defects in manufactured products and avoiding problems when delivering solutions or services to customers.

skills.name: software-qa-testing
skills.description: Software testing is an investigation conducted to provide stakeholders with information about the quality of the product or service under test.

skills.name: seo
skills.description: "Search engine optimization (SEO) is the process of improving the visibility of a website or a web page in search engines via the ""natural"" or un-paid (""organic"" or ""algorithmic"") search results."

skills.name: proofreading
skills.description: Proofreading (also proof-reading) is the reading of a galley proof or computer monitor to detect and correct production-errors of text or art. Proofreaders are expected to be consistently accurate by default because they occupy the last stage of typographic production before publication.

Proofreaders are expected to be consistently accurate by default because they occupy the last stage of typographic production before publication.
